Thanks to everyone who came out to MSU Billings today to have a frank conversation about the issues facing our state and our country. I always appreciate hearing from you and that you hold me accountable. I‚Äôm looking forward to seeing you at my next in-person town hall.

Took a question about dark money in our elections. Let‚Äôs be clear here, corporations aren‚Äôt people and Montanans know that. If you put a bill on the floor of the Senate that clarified that, it would pass.

Was just asked about civic engagement. The decisions we make today will have a tremendous impact on young people in this country. As leaders we can inspire the next generation by keeping politics out of our decision making and doing what‚Äôs right for the country. It‚Äôs that simple.

I just got a question about suicide rates in Montana. I've got a bill to address this crisis that would be a good start, but we have to keep pushing. We need more mental health professionals on the ground and we have to reduce the stigma around mental health in rural America.

Was just asked about our climate. We‚Äôve got ice sheets that are melting, we‚Äôve got oceans that are rising, we‚Äôve got bugs in our crops and in our forests that we've never had before. We have to work together to do something about our changing climate.

Just got a question about legislative gridlock in the Senate. We're supposed to be the greatest deliberative body in the world, but we don't debate much anymore. If we actually did the work of debating the issues, I think we'd come up with a whole heckuva lot more solutions.

One of the first questions is about protecting public lands. Let's be clear, one of the things that makes Montana great is our public lands. You don't have to be a millionaire and own a ranch to go hunting or a stream to go fishing. I'm always going to fight to keep it that way.
